The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.


<PREMISES>
All students are humans. 
If someone studies, then they are a student.
A person either studys or teaches.
No young person teaches.
Jerry neither teaches nor is a manager.
Rose is young or a student.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
True
</EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.


<PREMISES>
All students are humans. 
If someone studies, then they are a student.
A person either studys or teaches.
No young person teaches.
Jerry neither teaches nor is a manager.
Rose is young or a student.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
True
</EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.


<PREMISES>
All students are humans. 
If someone studies, then they are a student.
A person either studys or teaches.
No young person teaches.
Jerry neither teaches nor is a manager.
Rose is young or a student.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
True
</EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.


<PREMISES>
All students are humans. 
If someone studies, then they are a student.
A person either studys or teaches.
No young person teaches.
Jerry neither teaches nor is a manager.
Rose is young or a student.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
True
</EVALUATE>

The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.

A person either studys or teaches.

</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>

True
</EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.


<PREMISES>
All students are humans. 
If someone studies, then they are a student.
A person either studys or teaches.
No young person teaches.
Jerry neither teaches nor is a manager.
Rose is young or a student.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
True
</EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to evaluate the conclusion as 'True', 'False', or 'Uncertain' given the premises.


<PREMISES>
All students are humans. 
If someone studies, then they are a student.
A person either studys or teaches.
No young person teaches.
Jerry neither teaches nor is a manager.
Rose is young or a student.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Rose is a human or Jerry is a manager.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>
True
</EVALUATE>
